text:
8/8

Again, this is what it looks like to me. YMMV. IANAL.

I do have some real data that supports my opinion, but I've also been yelled at for this opinion in the past, so do with it what you will.

I'm right though... and bacon is delicious.

7/n

A lot of the things we tell undergrads to do—like get research experience—are really ways up moving up the technology tree, as it were. They make it more likely that you will go to "good" place or get letters from "good" people, etc.

6/n

• "you have none of that but you have good credentials otherwise" (you ain't getting in with a 2.3 and MAYBE you'll get in with perfect GRE scores and a high GPA from a place we don't trust or know)

5/n 

• "we don't know you and you don't have letters from folks we know, but *you* come from really good places we trust" (we may ask folks at those places we know) whether those places are your school or your internships or your job

4/n

• "we don't know you but you have letters from folks we know and respect" is next, followed by

• "we don't know you and you don't have letters from folks we know, but they come from really good places we trust" (we may ask folks there we know)

3/n

• "we know you" is the best option, assuming our view is positive (hence why GT undergrads with 2.3s can get into our prestigious program if we've known the student and decide the student is worth our money and time)

@ibogost @emayfarris This makes me think of accommodations for students with special needs. Many universities have entire systems set up to document and present these things, presumably in part because they aren’t rare across the whole student body and they want consistency.

Is this a good thing?

@rajmundn_ml @milad_Roygari At bottom, theorems have preconditions and we have to run experiments to see if we are in those preconditions. 

Note that I’m just talking about the technical question... which isn’t even really the real issue here.

@rajmundn_ml @milad_Roygari There are at least two possible problems. 1) the pixel values one would get with a different distribution of inputs might cause different behavior in the algorithm. 2) balancing categories if there are a lot of categories might make the learning problem harder.

@rajmundn_ml @milad_Roygari Not to get into this, but we do not know that he was “factually correct”. The assertion is actually an empirical one. It may seem obvious that “fixing” the dataset as described would “fix” the problem, but running the experiment is still necessary.

A bouquet is rarely a random bunch of flowers drawn from a stationary distribution with replacement.

I *do* think it’s a mistake to not reflect on all the very many places where bias—inductive or otherwise—can sneak in. There are both ethical and scientific reasons for doing so, if you allow me to make the distinction.

One doesn’t have to have an ideological desire in pointing out that this choice isn’t just a choice about data and may have downstream effects.

@davidthewid Anyway, I think the current access to... everything... is clearly a huge win. It almost certainly makes for better work overall, but life is always full of trade-offs.

@davidthewid Also, not for nothing, but sometimes “rediscovering” an idea has led to said idea having a greater impact than it did originally. A not small part of 1980s, 1990s ML involved discovering ideas that had already been figured out by statistics, or so many argued at the time.

@davidthewid The short answer: it can shut down extending lines of research. I’ve certainly had to talk my students down from the “I thought i had something but it has already been done, I’m useless” spiral, but it’s worse than that if thinking it’s already been done ends inquiry prematurely.
